<?xml version='1.0' encoding='UTF-8'?>
<worksheet>
  <title>Mathematics 204 Linear independence (Section 2.4)</title>
  <objectives>
    <introduction>
      <p>Make sure you can answer the following questions:</p>
    </introduction>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <p>What does it mean for a set of vectors to be linearly
 dependent or independent?</p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>How do the pivots of a matrix tell us about the linear
 independence/dependence of its columns?</p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>What is the largest possible number of vectors in a linearly
 independent set in <m>\real^n</m>?</p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>How do the solutions to the equation <m>A\xvec=\zerovec</m> give
 information about the linear independence/dependence of the
 columns of <m>A</m>?</p>
      </li>
    </ul>
  </objectives>
  <exercise>
    <task workspace="1.5in">
      <p>Consider the matrices 
 <md>
 A = 
 \left[
 \begin{array}{cccc}
 3 \amp 0 \amp -1 \amp 1 \\
 1 \amp -1 \amp 3 \amp 7 \\
 3 \amp -2 \amp 1 \amp 5 \\
 -1 \amp 2 \amp 2 \amp 3 \\
 \end{array}
 \right],~~~
 B = 
 \left[
 \begin{array}{cccc}
 3 \amp 0 \amp -1 \amp 4 \\
 1 \amp -1 \amp 3 \amp -1 \\
 3 \amp -2 \amp 1 \amp 3 \\
 -1 \amp 2 \amp 2 \amp 1 \\
 \end{array}
 \right].
 </md>
 Are the columns of <m>A</m> linearly independent? Are the columns
 of <m>B</m> linearly independent? Explain your thinking.</p>
    </task>
    <task workspace="1.25in">
      <p>For the matrix above whose columns are linearly dependent,
 express one of the vectors as a linear combination of the others.</p>
    </task>
  </exercise>
  <exercise workspace="1in">
    <statement>
      <p>Are the three vectors below linearly independent or dependent?
 Explain your thinking.
 [IMAGE: figures/lin-dep.pdf]</p>
    </statement>
  </exercise>
  <exercise>
    <task workspace="1.5in">
      <p>If <m>\vvec_1,\vvec_2,\vvec_3</m> is a set of vectors in
 <m>\real^5</m>, what is the shape of the matrix
 <m>\begin{bmatrix}\vvec_1 \amp \vvec_2 \amp \vvec_3 \end{bmatrix}</m> (that is,
 how many rows and columns)? If the set of vectors is linearly
 independent, what can you say about the pivot positions?</p>
    </task>
    <task workspace="1.25in">
      <p>Explain why seven vectors in <m>\real^5</m> cannot be linearly
 independent.</p>
    </task>
    <task workspace="1.25in">
      <p>What is the largest number of vectors in <m>\real^5</m> that can be
 linearly independent?</p>
    </task>
    <task workspace="1in">
      <p>If you have three vectors in <m>\real^5</m>, can you guarantee that they
 are linearly independent?</p>
    </task>
  </exercise>
  <exercise>
    <introduction>
      <p>If <m>A</m> is a matrix, we call the equation <m>A\xvec=\zerovec</m> a
 <em>homogeneous equation</em> since the right hand side is the zero
 vector. Explain why this equation is always consistent.</p>
    </introduction>
    <task workspace="2in">
      <p>Suppose that 
 <m>
 A = 
 \begin{bmatrix}
 3 \amp 0 \amp -1 \amp 4 \\
 1 \amp -1 \amp 3 \amp -3 \\
 3 \amp -2 \amp 1 \amp 0 \\
 -1 \amp 2 \amp 2 \amp -1
 \end{bmatrix}
 </m>. Write the solutions to the equation <m>A\xvec=\zerovec</m> in
 vector-parametric form.</p>
    </task>
    <task workspace="1.25in">
      <p>If the columns of <m>A</m> are <m>\vvec_1</m>, <m>\vvec_2</m>, <m>\vvec_3</m>, and
 <m>\vvec_4</m>, use your solution to this homogeneous equation to find
 one set of weights such that
 <md>
 c_1\vvec_1+c_2\vvec_2+c_3\vvec_3+c_4\vvec_4 = \zerovec
 </md>
 where at least one of the weights is nonzero.</p>
    </task>
    <task workspace="1.25in">
      <p>Use this expression to rewrite <m>\vvec_4</m> as a linear combination of
 the others.</p>
    </task>
    <task workspace="1.25in">
      <p>Is the set of vectors <m>\vvec_1</m>, <m>\vvec_2</m>, <m>\vvec_3</m>, <m>\vvec_4</m>
 linearly dependent or independent?</p>
    </task>
  </exercise>
  <exercise>
    <task workspace="1in">
      <p>Suppose that <m>\wvec_1</m>, <m>\wvec_2</m>, and <m>\wvec_3</m> are the columns
 of a matrix <m>B</m> and that
 <md>
 \wvec_3 = 2\wvec_1 - 3\wvec_2.
 </md>
 Is this set of vectors linearly dependent or independent?</p>
    </task>
    <task workspace="1in">
      <p>Explain why we can find a set of weights <m>c_1</m>, <m>c_2</m>, and <m>c_3</m>,
 not all of which are zero, for which
 <md>
 c_1\wvec_1+c_2\wvec_2 + c_3\wvec_3 = \zerovec.
 </md>
      </p>
    </task>
    <task workspace="1in">
      <p>Explain why there are infinitely many solutions to the homogeneous
 equation <m>B\xvec=\zerovec</m>.</p>
    </task>
    <task workspace="1in">
      <p>What does this say about the pivot positions of <m>B</m>?</p>
    </task>
  </exercise>
  <exercise>
    <task workspace="1in">
      <p>Suppose that <m>\vvec_1, \vvec_2, \ldots, \vvec_n</m> are vectors in
 <m>\real^{24}</m> that are linearly independent and that span <m>\real^{24}</m>.
 What can you say about the pivot positions of the matrix <m>A</m> whose
 columns are <m>\vvec_1, \vvec_2, \ldots, \vvec_n</m>?</p>
    </task>
    <task workspace="1in">
      <p>How many vectors are there in this set?</p>
    </task>
    <task workspace="1in">
      <p>Suppose that <m>\bvec</m> is a vector in <m>\real^{24}</m>. Explain how you
 know that <m>\bvec</m> can be written as a linear combination of
 <m>\vvec_1,\vvec_2, \ldots,\vvec_n</m>.</p>
    </task>
    <task workspace="1in">
      <p>Suppose that <m>\bvec</m> is a vector in <m>\real^{24}</m>. Explain how you
 know that <m>\bvec</m> can be written as a linear combination of
 <m>\vvec_1,\vvec_2, \ldots,\vvec_n</m> in exactly one way.</p>
    </task>
  </exercise>
  <exercise>
    <task workspace="1in">
      <p>Suppose that <m>\vvec_1,\vvec_2,\ldots,\vvec_n</m> are a set of
 vectors and that <m>\vvec_3</m> is a scalar multiple of <m>\vvec_7</m>. What
 can you say about the linear independence/dependence of this set of
 vectors?</p>
    </task>
    <task workspace="1in">
      <p>If <m>\vvec_1,\vvec_2,\ldots,\vvec_n</m> is a linearly independent set of
 vectors, is it necessarily true that one vector is a scalar multiple
 of another one?</p>
    </task>
  </exercise>
  <exercise>
    <task workspace="1in">
      <p>Suppose that <m>A</m> is a matrix such that the equation
 <m>A\xvec=\bvec</m> has exactly one solution for every vector <m>\bvec</m>.
 What can you say about the linear dependence/independence of the
 columns of <m>A</m>?</p>
    </task>
    <task workspace="1in">
      <p>What can you say about the span of the columns of <m>A</m>?</p>
    </task>
  </exercise>
</worksheet>

